SIMPLE: frit
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Frit
<hw>Frit</hw> <pr>(fr⟦icr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>fritte</ets>, fr. <ets>frit</ets> fried, p. p. of <ets>frire</ets>
to fry. See <er>Far</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Glass Making)</fld> <def>The material of which glass is made,
after having been calcined or partly fused in a furnace, but before
vitrification. It is a composition of silex and alkali, occasionally
with other ingredients.</def> <rj><au>Ure.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Ceramics)</fld> <def>The material for glaze of
pottery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Frit brick</b></col>, <cd>a lump of calcined glass
materials, brought to a pasty condition in a reverberatory furnace,
preliminary to the perfect vitrification in the melting
pot.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Frit
<hw>Frit</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Fritted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fritting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To prepare by heat (the
materials for making glass); to fuse partially.</def>
<rj><au>Ure.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Frit
<hw>Frit</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To fritter; -- with away.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Ld. Lytton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fritfly</ent>⟦br⟧
